{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_flatheadsole_ver01/data/sn95063172/00414185733/1930120601/0554.xml":{"full_text":"VOL. X NO. 45\nTHE KUSKO TIMES\nTAKOTNA ALAHKA. KATUHDAY. DR3EMHICU <5 MilMi\nJ i .n, i \u00bb\u25a0\u25a0'\u25a0'JifSaigigBL1...1 11. \u00bbJg*!I1.?*\"\nI'UJOK 25 OftNTH\nCongress\nConvenes\nWITH COMMUNISTS AND POLICE\nBATTLING OUTSIDE OF CAP\nITOE BUILDING\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 2^-Cengresx\nconvened Monday, with much fist\nfighting between communists and the\npolice on the outside of the building\nas the session opened.\nIn the rivers and harbors bill only\n$22,500 is estimated for the next fis\ncal year on Alaska projects, and all\nof it is for maintenance of*the Nome\nharbor. New projects for Ketchikan\nharbor, Port Alerander arid Seward\n\nharbor are listed for postponement,\nand no work is contemplated at Tolo\nvana harbor, recently adopted for im\nprovement. Likewise, there will be\nI no expenditures for Wrangell harbor\nand narrows.\nL DOESN\u2019T LIKE SALMON\nTREATY WITH CANADA\n_ i\n.SEATTLE, Dec. 5\u2014Governor Hart\nley announced last night that will\nI urge President Hoover to withdraw\nthe salmon treaty with Canada, now\nbefore the Senate for ratification.\nMELLON SAYS BUSINESS\nREVIVAL IN MIDSUMMER\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 5\u2014 Secretary\nof the Treasury Mellon, in iu\u00bb annual\nreport to Congress today, indicated\nthat there will be a revival of busi\nness in nrcidsnwmier.\nMYSTERIOUS POISON GAS IN\nMEUSE VALLEY KILLS 64\nBRUSSELS, Dec. \u20ac-\u2022\u2014A mysterious\npoison gas,, which had blanketed the\nMeuse valley for over a week, caused\nthe dentL of sixty-four person* and\nmany heads of livestock.\nVt ARKANSAS AND 7 KEN\nTUCKY BANKS SUSPEND\nPEND PAYMENTS FIVE DAYS\nCHICAGO.\u2014Thirty-nine banks in\nArkansas Monday suspended pay\nments to depositors for five days un\nder the state law allowing that time.\nTwo other Arkansas banks closed\nfor liquidation.\nSeven Kentucky banks closed as a\nprecautionary measure, while during\nthe past fortnight four Tennessee\nbanks have closed. Since Saturday\nfive Illinois banks have closed. Four\nsmall banks in Missouri closed on\nMonday.\nFIEND ATTEMPTS J O \u00abKECK\nHOSPITAL WITH EXPLOSION\nCHICAGO.\u2014Passible death oj in\njury of seventy nuns and patients in\nSt. Mary's hospital wa> narrowly\naverted early Sunday when an at\ntendant came upon the body of John\nWeber, night fireman, slumped on\nthe floor of the engine room near the\ndry and steaming boiler. Weber had\nbeen shot to death.\nThe large boiler had apparently\nbeen purposely drained of water and\nwar on the verge of an explosion.\nPolice said they believed a plot to\nblow up the hospital had been frus\ntrated. with little time to spare. They\nbelieve the plotter let the water from\nthe boiler, knowing it would blow up,\nand started search for a man with\nwhom the slain fireman had quarreled\nwhen he was discharged. The man\nsaid the mother superior he would\n\u2022*th\u00bbw up the place.\u201d\nTo Relieve\nUnemployed\nIfOOVKR\u2019H RKCOM M KN OATIONH\nfIMI'LY EXFENIMTUHK OF\n$650,ooo,aoo.\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 2. Poised\nfor immediate aetiqn, Congress today\nreceived from Hoover his rwummcn.\ndations that unemployment he afford\ned relief and that relief legislation\nhe given priority.\nThe President in his message also\nasked authority to make increased\ntemporary advances for federal road\naid, toguther with the request for\n15QJW0JM0 to expedite construction\nand provide work. .Such action, the\nPresident said, \u201cwill imply an ex\npenditure of more than $650,000,000\nJames J. Davis, former H<\u00abretary\nof Labor, was seated as Senator from\nPennsylvania today, over the protest\nof the Senate's campaign fund com\nmittee, pending an investigation as\nto the amount of money the Senator\nelect had spent in his campaign.\nNRSERV FOB ORPHANS AND\nOTHER CHILDREN, NENANA\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 20. \u2014John\nCooper, Commissioner of Education,\nin his general report to Sec/etary of\nInterior Wilbur today, announced\nthat one of the buildings at Fort Gib\nbon, Alaska, has been transformed\ninto a nursery for Alaska orphans\nand other children too young to at\ntend schouL\nWORLli COURT PR</rOCOL.\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 29. Presb\ndent Hoover announced yesterday\ntha. be will submit tl\u00bbe revised prot\nocol of the world -ourt to the Senate\nfor ratification at ti e December ses\nsion.\nMEL DAUGHERTY, HK'/IHEK\nOF FORMER ATTORNEY GEN\nERAL, INDICTED, 5b COL'NTS\nWASHINGTON COURT HOUSE,\nO., I>ec. S'.\u2014Mai Daugherty, brother\nof former Attorney General Harry\nDaugherty, and president of tike de\nfunct Ohio State Hank a*, this place,\nhat been indicted on bfc counts charg\ning embezzlement, misapplication of\nfunds and falsification of the bank\u2019s\ncondition. He is chargee with mis\nappropriating\nAERIAL SMUGGLERS INDICT\nED; 80 AIRPLANES USED\nDETROIT.*\u2014Operation. of two\naerial smuggling syndicates whose\nplanes brought liquor and aliens\nfrom Gatiada was revealed in the in\ndictment of ten inei by a federal\ngrand jury.\nGovernment information said the\nsyndicates operated thirty planet,\ntaking off in Canada and iandign on\nremote fields in the United States, it\nwas said the planes lauded contra\nhand in the vicinity of Oliio, Indiana\nand Illinois cities.\nThe evidence was obtained by un\ndercover agents who joined at he ago*\ndicats and worked with the smug\nglers for several weeks.\nMax Simel, well known oldtiiner\nand pioneer tradei who now conducts\na trading station at Eairview, on the\nInnoko river, was a Thursday arrival\nhere to give attention to a few busi\nness matters. He leporte conditions\nfairly quiet over in his section. He\nleft for Ophir yesterday, beaded for\nreturn to his headquarters.\nMKH. I.KONK C. HOW I,KM\nWAS MIIKDKHIO, AHHKKTM\nCOItOM'K\u2019H JIIMY. POKTbAM*\nPORTLAND, f.\u00ab\u00ab\u00bb\u2022\u00ab\nC. Howh-s was murdered, either by\nIrrna llhtwku or Nelson <3. liowleo,\nher husband, or by both, was the ver\ndiet return